# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: afl-reserves
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:afl-reserves/1897-vfl-season] The **1897 VFL season** was the inaugural season of the Victorian Football League (VFL), the highest-level senior Australian rules football competition in Victoria.
[src:afl-reserves/1897-vfl-season] The season ran from 8 May to 4 September, comprising a 14-round home-and-away season followed by a three-week finals series featuring the top four clubs.
[src:afl-reserves/1897-vfl-season] Eight Victorian Football Association (VFA) clubs – Carlton, Collingwood, Essendon, Fitzroy, Geelong, Melbourne, South Melbourne and St Kilda – featured in the inaugural season after seceding from the VFA in 1896.
[src:afl-reserves/1897-vfl-season] Essendon won the inaugural premiership after winning all three of its finals matches, with Geelong finishing as runners-up with two wins.
[src:afl-reserves/1897-vfl-season] Geelong won the minor premiership by finishing atop the home-and-away ladder with an 11–3 win–loss record.
[src:afl-reserves/1897-vfl-season] Geelong's Eddy James and Melbourne's Jack Leith tied for the leading goalkicker medal as the league's leading goalkickers.
[src:afl-reserves/1897-vfl-season] In 1897, the VFL competition consisted of eight teams of 20 on-the-field players each, with no "reserves" (although any of the 20 players who had left the playing field for any reason could later resume their place on the field at any time during the match).
[src:afl-reserves/1897-vfl-season] Each team played each other twice in a home-and-away season of 14 rounds.
[src:afl-reserves/1897-vfl-season] Once the 14-round home-and-away season had finished, the 1897 VFL Premiers were determined according to the conditions dictated by the specific format and conventions of the 1897 Finals System, which was used in this season only.
[src:afl-reserves/1897-vfl-season] The following table can be sorted from biggest winning margin to biggest losing margin for each round.
[src:afl-reserves/1897-vfl-season] If two or more matches in a round are decided by the same margin, these margins are sorted by percentage (i.e. the lowest-scoring winning team is ranked highest and the lowest-scoring losing team is ranked lowest).
[src:afl-reserves/1897-vfl-season] Opponents are listed above the margins and home matches are in bold.
[src:afl-reserves/1898-vfl-grand-final] The **1898 VFL Grand Final** was an Australian rules football game contested between the Essendon Football Club and Fitzroy Football Club, held in Melbourne on 24 September 1898.
[src:afl-reserves/1898-vfl-grand-final] The match was played to determine the premiers for the 1898 VFL season.
[src:afl-reserves/1898-vfl-grand-final] The game was played under atrocious ground conditions in front of 16,538 people at the Junction Oval.
[src:afl-reserves/1898-vfl-grand-final] The match is recognised as the first VFL grand final, although the term "grand final" was not in wide use until 1931.
[src:afl-reserves/1898-vfl-grand-final] It was the first time that Victorian Football League premiership was decided in a final match, as the 1897 premiership was won under a different finals system by Essendon when they finished above three other clubs on the finals series ladder.
[src:afl-reserves/1898-vfl-grand-final] Both Fitzroy back pocket Stan Reid and the Essendon full-forward Charlie Moore later died in South Africa in active service during the Anglo-Boer War—Moore on 5 May 1901, and Reid on 23 June 1901.
[src:afl-reserves/1898-vfl-grand-final] During the 1898 home-and-away season, all teams played each other twice.
[src:afl-reserves/1898-vfl-grand-final] The winners of the two sections were Fitzroy and Collingwood, respectively (for results of all of the round-robin matches); and, a week later (17 September 1898), the two teams played each other at Brunswick Street Oval, with Fitzroy winning the match 2.10 (22) to 1.5 (11).
[src:afl-reserves/1898-vfl-grand-final] After the VFL referred the decision to the VFL's Match Arrangement Committee, they, upon the express instructions of that committee, rejected the suggestions of the two teams outright and the match was controversially scheduled to be played at the Junction Oval.
[src:afl-reserves/1898-vfl-grand-final] The Junction Oval was in an appalling condition, as the ground had not been used since the second Saturday of the sectional round-robin match three weeks earlier (3 September); and, since then, it had been thoroughly top-dressed and "cultivated" in anticipation of the coming cricket season.
[src:afl-reserves/1898-vfl-grand-final] Also, the cricket ground's asphalt cycling track that lay between the boundary line and the fence presented a considerable danger to the footballers.
[src:afl-reserves/1898-vfl-grand-final] Despite being the "challenger", Essendon flatly refused to play in the scheduled match, declaring that it would rather forfeit the match and the premiership than play on such a dangerous surface.
[src:afl-reserves/1898-vfl-grand-final] This view was also strongly supported by Fitzroy, whose captain, Alec Sloan, had also taken the step of signing a statutory declaration to the effect that, in his opinion, the ground was entirely unfit to play on.
[src:afl-reserves/1898-vfl-grand-final] The VFL, perhaps somewhat driven by the fact that the attraction of a finals system was one of the major reasons that the eight teams had left the VFA and formed the VFL in the first place, had a special meeting to hear Essendon's appeal.
[src:afl-reserves/1898-vfl-grand-final] While it chose to endorse the committee's decision, it also did everything it could to convince Essendon to play the match.
[src:afl-reserves/1898-vfl-grand-final] Essendon did not actually agree to play the match until the night before the game; ultimately, this "in-doubt-until-the-last-minute match" was still attended by 16,538 paying spectators; it certainly would have been a much larger crowd otherwise.
[src:afl-reserves/1898-vfl-grand-final] The ground had been in such a dreadful condition that, in the week prior to the match, over 40 dray-loads of rubbish, soil and street-sweepings had been taken from the ground.
[src:afl-reserves/1898-vfl-grand-final] All of this last-minute work greatly improved the playing surface at the ground, with sportswriters noting that while the ground was imperfect, it was nevertheless fit for use.
[src:afl-reserves/1898-vfl-grand-final] Dry, windy weather and patches of ground where the topsoil had not bound meant that players often fell on the grassless slippery ground for want of some sort of grip, and play was often impeded by clouds of dust.
[src:afl-reserves/1898-vfl-grand-final] To prevent any repeat of the events leading up to the 1898 challenge final, the VFL agreed that from 1899 they would schedule for a possible challenge final in advance.
[src:afl-reserves/1898-vfl-grand-final] In 1898, all VFL teams had 20 on-the-field players and no "reserves".
[src:afl-reserves/1898-vfl-grand-final] Although there were no reserves, any player who had left the playing field for any reason at all could resume his place on the field at any time.
[src:afl-reserves/1898-vfl-grand-final] Fitzroy selected a set of brothers in its team: Jim and Mick Grace (see TALK page).
[src:afl-reserves/1898-vfl-grand-final] Essendon had beaten Fitzroy in their round 1 and round 8 matches by 53 and 43 points, respectively.
[src:afl-reserves/1898-vfl-grand-final] Fitzroy had beaten Essendon by 29 points in the third match of their round-robin Sectional matches.
[src:afl-reserves/1898-vfl-grand-final] Both teams had great difficulty playing football in the appalling ground conditions—as evidenced by the low scores—and the tough, bustling Fitzroy team handled the conditions far better than the Essendon team that had hoped to spread the game out as far as possible.
[src:afl-reserves/1898-vfl-grand-final] Fitzroy took the lead in the first few minutes of the match, and Essendon were never able to catch up.
[src:afl-reserves/1898-vfl-grand-final] Essendon were further demoralized when Fitzroy champion forward and follower Mick Grace, renowned for his marking skill and kicking prowess, flew high over a pack to take a spectacular high mark and kicked a long-range goal.
[src:afl-reserves/1898-vfl-grand-final] In a very tight, defensive second half, as the playing conditions deteriorated even further, only one goal was scored.
[src:afl-reserves/1898-vfl-grand-final] Fitzroy went on to beat Essendon 5.8 (38) to 3.5 (23).
[src:afl-reserves/1898-vfl-season] The **1898 VFL season** was the second season of the Victorian Football League (VFL), the highest-level senior Australian rules football competition in Victoria.
[src:afl-reserves/1898-vfl-season] The season featured eight clubs and ran from 14 May to 24 September, comprising a 14-round home-and-away season followed by a finals series featuring all eight clubs.
[src:afl-reserves/1898-vfl-season] Fitzroy won the premiership, defeating Essendon by 15 points in the 1898 VFL grand final; it was Fitzroy's first VFL premiership.
[src:afl-reserves/1898-vfl-season] Essendon won the minor premiership by finishing atop the home-and-away ladder with an 11–3 win–loss record.
[src:afl-reserves/1898-vfl-season] Collingwood's Archie Smith won the leading goalkicker medal as the league's leading goalkicker.
[src:afl-reserves/1898-vfl-season] In 1898, the VFL competition consisted of eight teams of 20 on-the-field players each, with no "reserves" (although any of the 20 players who had left the playing field for any reason could later resume their place on the field at any time during the match).
[src:afl-reserves/1898-vfl-season] Once the 14 round home-and-away season had finished, the 1898 VFL *Premiers* were determined by the specific format and conventions of the 1898 VFL finals system.
[src:afl-reserves/1898-vfl-season] The VFL introduced a new system of finals for the 1898 season.
[src:afl-reserves/1898-vfl-season] The new system, which was used from 1898–1900, allowed all clubs to compete for the major premiership, with the minor premiers having the right to challenge for the premiership.
[src:afl-reserves/1898-vfl-season] By winning the minor premiership and accruing at least eight premiership points from its three sectional matches, Essendon won the right to challenge the semi-final winner for the premiership.
[src:afl-reserves/1899-vfl-grand-final] It was the second annual grand final of the Victorian Football League.
[src:afl-reserves/1899-vfl-grand-final] The match, attended by 4,823 spectators, was won by Fitzroy by a margin of 1 point, becoming the first club to claim back-to-back VFL premierships.
[src:afl-reserves/1899-vfl-grand-final] Fitzroy had won the minor premiership in the 1899 season, while South Melbourne had finished sixth after the home-and-away season.
[src:afl-reserves/1899-vfl-grand-final] In the sectional major rounds, Fitzroy and South Melbourne each finished with records of 3–0 to qualify for the final.
[src:afl-reserves/1899-vfl-grand-final] Under the finals system in place, this match was the final of the major round, played between the two section winners.
[src:afl-reserves/1899-vfl-grand-final] Had South Melbourne won the match, it would not have immediately won the season's premiership; Fitzroy, as the minor premiers, would have had the right to challenge South to a rematch for the premiership on the following Saturday.
[src:afl-reserves/1899-vfl-grand-final] Meanwhile, Fitzroy could clinch the premiership win a win in this match.
[src:afl-reserves/1899-vfl-grand-final] "The last match of the season for the league premiership was played on Saturday, when Fitzroy and South Melbourne met on the St.
[src:afl-reserves/1899-vfl-grand-final] Unfortunately, steady rain, which had fallen all the morning, continued nearly all the afternoon, making the conditions under which the game was played unsatisfactory for the players and most unpleasant for spectators.
[src:afl-reserves/1899-vfl-grand-final] The "weather committee" had not met to consider the advisability of a postponement, and when the teams assembled South Melbourne suggested deferring the match until next Saturday, but Fitzroy preferred to brave the elements.
[src:afl-reserves/1899-vfl-grand-final] The assembling of about 4000 spectators in the unfavorable circumstances indicated clearly that, if the weather had kept fine, the attendance would have been enormous.
[src:afl-reserves/1899-vfl-grand-final] As it was, those present evinced keen interest in the game, every notable bit of good play being heartily cheered.
[src:afl-reserves/1899-vfl-grand-final] Amongst the onlookers were a number of enthusiasts from Geelong, who came up by special train.
[src:afl-reserves/1899-vfl-grand-final] had the ground in splendid order until the rain came, and even after the steady downpour, extending over many hours, it played very, much better than could have been expected, reflecting great credit on the experienced and skilful curator. ...
[src:afl-reserves/1899-vfl-grand-final] The strong wind from the southern end of the ground favoured South Melbourne in the opening quarter.
[src:afl-reserves/1899-vfl-grand-final] Harry Lampe kicked the first two goals of the match, and Fitzroy's only score, a behind, came when a kick from Mick Grace hit the post.
[src:afl-reserves/1899-vfl-grand-final] Fitzroy then had the advantage of the wind in the second quarter.
[src:afl-reserves/1899-vfl-grand-final] Goals to Mick Grace and Fred Fontaine had them ahead at half time.
[src:afl-reserves/1899-vfl-grand-final] Charlie Colgan gave South Melbourne the lead with the only goal of the third term.
[src:afl-reserves/1899-vfl-grand-final] Bill McSpeerin's goal 15 minutes into the final quarter gave Fitzroy the win.
[src:afl-reserves/1899-vfl-grand-final] Fitzroy's Bert Sharpe, the team's centre half-forward in its 1898 premiership side, was a late withdrawal from the side due to the death of his father the day before the Grand Final; his teammates wore black armbands for that match.
[src:afl-reserves/1899-vfl-season] The **1899 VFL season** was the third season of the Victorian Football League (VFL), the highest-level senior Australian rules football competition in Victoria.
[src:afl-reserves/1899-vfl-season] The season featured eight clubs and ran from 13 May to 16 September, comprising a 14-round home-and-away season followed by a finals series featuring all eight clubs.
[src:afl-reserves/1899-vfl-season] Fitzroy won the premiership, defeating South Melbourne by one point in the 1899 VFL grand final; it was Fitzroy's second (consecutive and overall) VFL premiership.
[src:afl-reserves/1899-vfl-season] Fitzroy also won the minor premiership by finishing atop the home-and-away ladder with an 11–3 win–loss record.
[src:afl-reserves/1899-vfl-season] Geelong's Eddy James won his second leading goalkicker medal as the league's leading goalkicker.
[src:afl-reserves/1899-vfl-season] In 1899, the VFL competition consisted of eight teams of 18 on-the-field players each, with no "reserves" (although any of the 18 players who had left the playing field for any reason could later resume their place on the field at any time during the match).
[src:afl-reserves/1899-vfl-season] Once the 14 round home-and-away season had finished, the 1899 VFL *Premiers* were determined by the specific format and conventions of the 1898 VFL finals system.
[src:afl-reserves/1900-vfl-grand-final] The **1900 VFL Grand Final** was an Australian rules football game contested between the Melbourne Football Club and Fitzroy Football Club, held at the East Melbourne Cricket Ground in Melbourne on 22 September 1900.
[src:afl-reserves/1900-vfl-grand-final] It was the 3rd annual Grand Final of the Victorian Football League, staged to determine the premiers for the 1900 VFL season.
[src:afl-reserves/1900-vfl-grand-final] The match, attended by 20,181 spectators, was won by Melbourne by a margin of 4 points.
[src:afl-reserves/1900-vfl-grand-final] The winner of this match would win the premiership.
[src:afl-reserves/1900-vfl-grand-final] Arthur Sowden, and Bill Bowe were unable to play for the Melbourne team, due to injury, and Eric Gardner was unavailable.
[src:afl-reserves/1900-vfl-season] The **1900 VFL season** was the fourth season of the Victorian Football League (VFL), the highest-level senior Australian rules football competition in Victoria.
[src:afl-reserves/1900-vfl-season] The season featured eight clubs and ran from 5 May to 22 September, comprising a 14-round home-and-away season followed by a finals series featuring all eight clubs.
[src:afl-reserves/1900-vfl-season] Melbourne won the premiership, defeating Fitzroy by four points in the 1900 VFL grand final; it was Melbourne's first VFL premiership.
[src:afl-reserves/1900-vfl-season] Fitzroy won its second consecutive minor premiership by finishing atop the home-and-away ladder with an 11–3 win–loss record.
[src:afl-reserves/1900-vfl-season] Geelong's Teddy Lockwood and Essendon's Albert Thurgood tied for the leading goalkicker medal as the league's leading goalkickers.
[src:afl-reserves/1900-vfl-season] In 1900, the VFL competition consisted of eight teams of 18 on-the-field players each, with no "reserves", although any of the 18 players who had left the playing field for any reason could later resume their place on the field at any time during the match.
[src:afl-reserves/1900-vfl-season] Once the 14 round home-and-away season had finished, the 1900 VFL *Premiers* were determined by the specific format and conventions of the 1898 VFL finals system.
[src:afl-reserves/1900-vfl-season] The rescheduling of round 3 until after round 14, which occurred following the cancellation of the originally scheduled matches due to heavy rain, is also reflected in this table.
[src:afl-reserves/1900-vfl-season] By winning the minor premiership and accruing at least eight premiership points from its three sectional matches, Fitzroy won the right to challenge the semi-final winner for the premiership.
[src:afl-reserves/afl-reserves] The **AFL reserve grade competition**, commonly known simply as the **AFL reserves**, was an Australian rules football competition that operated as a second-tier competition to the Australian Football League (AFL) from 1919 until 1999.
[src:afl-reserves/afl-reserves] Prior to 1990, it was known as the **VFL reserve grade competition**, **VFL reserves** or **VFL seconds**.
[src:afl-reserves/afl-reserves] In its final season in 1999, the competition was made up of the reserves teams of all the senior AFL clubs that were based in Victoria, plus that of the Sydney Swans.
[src:afl-reserves/afl-reserves] Since 2000, the Victorian Football League (VFL), formerly known as the Victorian Football Association (VFA), has operated as a hybrid second-tier senior competition and reserves competition for most of the AFL clubs.
[src:afl-reserves/afl-reserves] In 1919, a new football competition known as the **Victorian Junior Football League** (**VJFL**) was established – at this time, junior was the term used for open age football of a lower standard than senior football, rather than for under age football.
[src:afl-reserves/afl-reserves] The league was intended to bring a junior club affiliated with each of the Victorian Football League (VFL) senior clubs into a single competition, and to adopt the same district eligibility scheme which the VFL had introduced in 1916.
[src:afl-reserves/afl-reserves] Player permit rules allowed for automatic transfers between the junior and senior clubs until July, allowing the juniors to serve as second eighteens for the seniors.
[src:afl-reserves/afl-reserves] The junior and senior clubs shared a home ground, with the juniors playing home when the seniors played away.
[src:afl-reserves/afl-reserves] University, which had left the VFL senior competition after 1914, also entered a stand-alone junior team in the competition.
[src:afl-reserves/afl-reserves] Shortly before the season, Caulfield withdrew, and a second University team was quickly arranged to take its place for the 1919 season.
[src:afl-reserves/afl-reserves] The two University teams were known as University A and University B, later becoming the modern day 'University Blues' and 'University Blacks'.
[src:afl-reserves/afl-reserves] University B contested only the 1919 season, with a Melbourne Juniors team established for 1920; University A contested the 1919 and 1920 seasons, reaching the grand final both years before dropping out.
[src:afl-reserves/afl-reserves] West Melbourne faced multiple heavy losses in 1920, including a 197-point loss against Carlton District and a 229-point loss against St Kilda District.
[src:afl-reserves/afl-reserves] The club left the competition at the end of the season, and were replaced by Essendon Juniors.
[src:afl-reserves/afl-reserves] In 1925, the VJFL was renamed as the **VFL seconds**, later known more commonly as the **VFL reserves**.
[src:afl-reserves/afl-reserves] Following the change, the seconds clubs still operated as distinct stand-alone clubs at this time, rather than coming directly under the influence of their senior clubs.
[src:afl-reserves/afl-reserves] This changed over the following decades, with all of the seconds teams gradually being subsumed by their senior counterparts.
[src:afl-reserves/afl-reserves] Melbourne won the 1931, 1932, 1933, 1934 and 1935 premierships - the only time in VFL/AFL history (seniors or reserves) that a club has won five grand finals in a row.
[src:afl-reserves/afl-reserves] History was made in 1991, with the Brisbane Bears winning the reserves premiership − the first non-Victorian club to win a VFL/AFL premiership in any grade.
[src:afl-reserves/afl-reserves] The Victorian State Football League was established at the end of 1991 to take over administration of football in Victoria from the Australian Football League, which was now becoming preoccupied with administration of the game nationally.
[src:afl-reserves/afl-reserves] The VSFL ran the AFL reserves competition from 1992 until 1999, which was also referred as the VSFL in its first few years.
[src:afl-reserves/afl-reserves] At the end of 1994, the VSFL also took over administration of the Victorian Football Association (VFA) competition (which was renamed the Victorian Football League in 1996).
[src:afl-reserves/afl-reserves] Following the 1999 season, the AFL reserves was merged into the Victorian Football League.
[src:afl-reserves/afl-reserves] Such a merger had first been proposed as early as 1980, and a formal attempt to enact the merger for the 1995 season was defeated after strong opposition from the clubs.
[src:afl-reserves/afl-reserves] South Melbourne was relocated to Sydney at the end of the 1981 VFL season, after which the club continued to play in the VFL/AFL reserves as Sydney.
[src:afl-reserves/afl-reserves] The Brisbane Bears competed for four years between 1989 and 1992, winning their only premiership at any grade in 1991.
[src:afl-reserves/afl-reserves] After their merger with Fitzroy at the end of 1996, the Brisbane Lions did not compete in the competition.
[src:afl-reserves/afl-reserves] No teams from South Australia or Western Australia ever competed in the VFL/AFL reserves.
[src:afl-reserves/afl-reserves] South Melbourne relocated to Sydney in 1982 was renamed Sydney Swans in 1983.
[src:afl-reserves/afl-reserves] Footscray was renamed Western Bulldogs in 1997.
[src:afl-reserves/afl-reserves] A number of notable players competed solely in the reserves competition.
[src:afl-reserves/afl-reserves] Shane Warne, considered to be one of the greatest bowlers in the history of cricket, played a single game for St Kilda in 1988: he was erroneously listed in the Record as Trevor Warne, and played in the Under-19s for the remainder of the season.
[src:afl-reserves/afl-reserves] Former St Kilda number one ticket holder John Moran also played for the reserves side.
[src:afl-reserves/afl-reserves] John Bourke, a Collingwood forward, infamously shoved an umpire and then attacked a fan among other incidents during a game in 1985, leading to a suspension of ten years plus 16 games, equivalent to 240 matches.
[src:afl-reserves/afl-reserves] Geelong won the most reserves premierships, with a total of 13.
